# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: association-football
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] The **12th man** or **12th player** is a collective term for fans of sports teams in many eleven-a-side games, in particular association football.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] As most football leagues allow a maximum of eleven players per team on the playing field at a time, referring to a team's fans as the 12th man implies that they have a potentially helpful and significant role in the game.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] The presence of fans can have a notable impact on teams' performance, an element in the home advantage.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Namely, the home team fans would vocally support and urge on their team to win the game.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Thus, these fans will often create loud sounds or chant in the hope of encouraging their team, or of distracting, demoralizing, or confusing the opposing team while they have possession of the ball, or to persuade a referee to make a favorable decision for the team.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Noises are made by shouting, singing, whistling, stomping, clapping, and various other techniques.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] In Canadian football, 12 players from each team are usually on the field at one time and the term **13th man** is often used to refer to fans.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Similarly, in Australian rules football, 18 players are on the field, and the fans are often referred to as the **19th man**.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] However, in basketball, where five players are on the court, the term *Sixth man* generally refers to an energetic substitute player.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Similarly, in rugby sevens, with seven players from each team on the field, "Eighth man" is not used to refer to fans as the term refers to the eighth forward in rugby union.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] The term *Twelfth Man* has a specifically different meaning in cricket, referring instead to the nominated first substitute player who fields when a member of the fielding side is injured during play.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] The first recorded use of the term "twelfth man" was a magazine published by the University of Minnesota in September 1900, that referred to "the mysterious influence of the twelfth man on the team, the rooter".
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Later, in the November 1912 edition of *The Iowa Alumnus*, an alumni publication of the University of Iowa (then known as State University of Iowa), E.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] McGowan described the 1903 game between Iowa and the University of Illinois.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] The 1922 Dixie Classic served as the setting for an event later referred to as "The story of the 12th Man".
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] This football game featured the top-ranked Centre College and The Agricultural and Mechanical College of Texas (later known as Texas A&M).
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Bible realized that one more injury would leave him without another backfield player to send into the game.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] King Gill, a sophomore basketball player, down from the stands to stand ready as a substitute.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Gill was ready in uniform on the sidelines if his team needed him.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Individuals have occasionally been labeled by local media as the "Twelfth Man" of their team.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Adamson, Principal of Oak Cliff (Dallas) High School was called the "Twelfth Man" of the school's American football team by a local reporter due to the rousing pre-game speeches he would give to the players.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Likewise, sometimes, fans of both teams in an annual contest have been described as the 12th man.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] The Bears currently use the phrase "4th Phase" (with the first three phases being offense, defense, and special teams), and the Seahawks currently use the phrase "The 12s".
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Many high schools in the United States incorporate 12th man language into their booster, supporter, or rooter clubs.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Examples of such "12th Man Clubs" include the Dana Hills Dolphins, Washington Panthers, Richwood Knights, Diamond Bar Brahmas, Fairfield Falcons, and Brentwood Bruins.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] The Campbellsville University Tigers of the National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics also have a 12th Man Club.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] On December 12, 1992, (12/12/1992) the Buffalo Bills of the National Football League honored their 12th Man as the seventh inductee into the Buffalo Bills Wall of Fame, located inside Highmark Stadium.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Their fans were inducted because of their loyal support during the team's early '90s Super Bowl runs, which coincided with quarterback Jim Kelly and his wearing of #12.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] In 2008, the Bills renamed their "12th Man Walk of Fame" as "Tim Russert Plaza", in honor of the recently deceased Buffalo native and lifelong fan.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] The team continues to refer to its fans as the "12th Man", with their independent, international fan clubs known as "Bills Backers Chapters".
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] The Bills have a licensing agreement with Texas A&M over the use of the "12th Man" term.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] From 2007 to 2016, fans of the Indianapolis Colts of the NFL were known as the 12th Man.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] The Colts created a Ring of Honor on September 23, 1996, after playing 13 seasons in Indianapolis, Indiana.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] In 2007, the Colts inducted their 12th Man as the sixth entrant into the team's Ring of Honor, then located on the interior facade of the RCA Dome.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] The Ring of Honor currently encircles Lucas Oil Stadium, the team's home venue.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] The organization also designates a "12th Man Fan of the Game".
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] On November 12, 2015, Texas A&M announced the filing of a lawsuit against the Colts based on the team's usage of the term.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] On February 17, 2016, the lawsuit was settled with the Colts agreeing to remove the phrase from their Ring of Honor and to immediately cease all other uses of the trademarked phrase.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] The Seattle Seahawks retired the number 12 jersey on December 15, 1984, in honor of their fans.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] In 2003, the Seahawks installed a giant flagpole in the south end zone of what is now Lumen Field, and began a tradition of raising a giant flag with the number 12 on it in honor of the fans, one of whom is Sam Adkins, the former Seahawks quarterback who did wear the number 12.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Usually, a local celebrity or a season ticket holder raises the flag during pregame ceremonies.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] In recent years, 12th Man flags have been seen all over Seattle whenever the Seahawks make the playoffs, including atop the Space Needle.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] In 2014, Boeing painted a Boeing 747-8 freighter aircraft with a special Seahawks livery, with the number 12 on the tail, and they later flew it over eastern Washington in a flight path spelling the number 12.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] When the Seahawks took the field for Super Bowl XLVIII, they were led by LB Heath Farwell carrying the team's 12th Man flag per team tradition.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] In May 2016, mountaineer David Liaño González displayed a 12th Man flag at the summit of Mount Everest.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] As per an agreement struck between the Seahawks and Texas A&M in 2016, the Seahawks have virtually ceased from referring to their fans as the "12th Man", and instead are using the term "12s" or the 12 Fan.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] The first known instance of Texas A&M referring to its fanbase as the "12th Man" is contained on page 17 of the November 25, 1921, edition of *The Battalion*, the Texas A&M campus newspaper.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] King Gill left the stands in 1922; the entire student body stood throughout the game to symbolize their "readiness, desire, and enthusiasm" to take the field if needed.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Football coach Jackie Sherrill created the "12th Man Kick-Off Team" in the 1980s, composed of non-athletic scholarship students who tried out for the team.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Coach Sherrill has written a book entitled "No Experience Required" which details this team and the tradition.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] These students were placed on the roster for the sole purpose of kickoffs.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] The squad was nicknamed "the suicide squad".
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] These students often had little regard for their safety and were determined to make a tackle at any cost.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] The 12th Man Kick-Off Team was extremely successful and eventually held opponents to one of the lowest yards-per-return average in the league during kickoffs.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Slocum changed the team to allow only one representative of the 12th Man on the kickoff team who wears uniform number 12.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] The player is chosen based on the level of determination and hard work shown in practices.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Under Dennis Franchione, the 12th Man Kick-Off Team, composed of walk-ons, was brought back, though used only rarely when the team was up by quite a few points.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] On June 30, 2014, Texas A&M bought the domain name 12thman.com, which then became its official athletics website.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] In 1986, the Washington Redskins (now known as the Washington Commanders) released a video entitled "Thanks to the 12th Man".
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] The term "12th man" is commonly used in football to refer to the fans and occasionally the manager.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] A notable club famous for the twelfth man reference comes from Aston Villa, referring to the Holte End stand at Villa Park.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Large European teams such as Bayern Munich, Malmö FF, Hammarby IF, Helsingborgs IF, Werder Bremen, Aberdeen, Rangers, Lazio, PSV, Feyenoord, Ferencvárosi TC, FC Red Star, Fenerbahçe S.K., and Sporting CP have officially retired the number 12 to the fans.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Stockport County fans are registered as official members of their squad with the number 12.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Portsmouth F.C. has also retired its number 12 shirt, and lists the club's supporters, "Pompey Fans", as player number 12 on the squad list printed in home match programmes, while Plymouth Argyle have theirs registered to the *Green Army* (the nickname for their fans).
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] On Hammarby IF's, Helsingborgs IF, Malmö FF, Feyenoord and Werder Bremen's home games, the stadium speaker announces number 12 as "the fans" during team lineup announcements.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Dynamo Dresden in Germany also keeps number 12 for their fans, as well as the official team anthem being "We are the 12th man".
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Aberdeen F.C. supporters commonly display a large banner in the shape of a football shirt with the text "Red Army 12" in place of a player's name and number.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] The fans of the Northern Ireland national football team and Derry City are referred to as the 12th man as well.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] In the League of Ireland, Shamrock Rovers F.C. retired the number 12 jersey in recognition of the fans who took over the club in 2005.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Cork City F.C., Clube Atlético Mineiro and Clube de Regatas do Flamengo also retired the number 12 for the fans.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] The most vociferous fans of Boca Juniors in Argentina are known as the "Jugador Numero 12" (Spanish for "Player Number 12") or simply "La Doce" ("The 12").
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Lecce, an Italian team currently playing in Serie B, retired the number 12 to the fans, which was handed to them by the former captain Cristian Ledesma.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] They symbolically represent a 12th Man in the field.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] In the beginning of 2009–2010 season, Happy Valley AA introduced the club's mascot, a panda, on squad list as the fan club captain wearing the number 12 jersey.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] As of the end of the 2011–2012 season, Rangers F.C announced that the number 12 jersey would be retired in honour of the fans support throughout a period of financial difficulty.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] In American football, the sideline is sometimes also referred to as the "12th man" or "12th defender": since a player is considered down when he steps out of bounds, the sideline effectively acts as an extra defender.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] This usage is less common than the one referring to the fans.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] In most sports the term can also be construed to mean the referee, implying that the match official favours one team and is not impartial.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] The effects of the "12th man" vary widely, but can be put in two categories.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] The first is simply psychological, the effect of showing the home team that they are appreciated, and showing the away team that they are somewhat unwelcome.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] The second directly relates to the deafening effects of a loud crowd.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] In Association football, the crowd can be very passionate and often sing throughout the whole match.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Some occasions where the crowd noise is extra loud can be before kickoff; during the buildup to and scoring of a goal; when encouraging the team to come back from defeat; to discourage an opposition penalty taker; or to harass a referee giving a free kick to the opposition team.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] In American football, fans are most incited by physical play, especially good plays made by the defense.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Additionally, the home team can derive energy from the loud noise of their fans; former American football players have described the feeling of their adrenaline pumping after hearing the fans yell, which is "like you have a reserve energy tank".
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] The noise of the crowd can have a significant impact on the players on the field.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] In American football, an extremely loud crowd can prevent the offensive linemen from hearing the snap count.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] This can have the effect of making the player slower to react when the ball is snapped, and his eventual response may be weaker than normal because each play is begun "with some indecision and doubt".
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] The noise can also prevent players from hearing audibles and can make it difficult for the team's offense to coordinate plays in the huddle.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] The effect of the noise can often be measured in mistakes, such as false start penalties.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Coaches can take steps to minimize the effect of the crowd noise on their teams.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Some American football teams bring large speakers to their practice fields and broadcast loud noises such as jet engines to prepare their teams for the anticipated noise level.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Crowd noise tends to diminish after a long lull in play, such as a pause for instant replay.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Former NFL player Brian Baldinger speculates that some coaches draw out reviews as part of a coaching strategy to quiet the crowd for their next play.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] A researcher from Harvard University discovered in a study that some association football referees appeared to be impacted by crowd noise.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] His studies revealed that a home team acquired an additional 0.1 goal advantage for every 10,000 fans in the stadium.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Delia Smith, Norwich City's joint major shareholder, received some attention when she took to the pitch during a half time interval, with a microphone in hand and Sky TV cameras in tow, to tell fans the side "need their twelfth man".
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Norwich City lost the game in the final seconds, but Smith's passion worked to increase the affection the fans held for her.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] The current naturally loudest football stadium is Nef Stadium in Istanbul home of Galatasaray S.K.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] As a prepared attempt, the current world record for crowd noise at an athletic event was set on September 29, 2014, when the Kansas City Chiefs hosted the New England Patriots.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Noise during that event reached a high of 142.2 decibels during a timeout.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Texas A&M University applied on December 26, 1989, for trademark U.S.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] The United States Patent and Trademark Office issued the "trademark registration" September 4, 1990, to Texas A&M.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Four additional Trademark claims related to the "12th Man" term were also filed and granted at later dates by Texas A&M University (See U.S.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] 74560726, 76671314, 85977835 and 85851199), the first three of which have achieved Incontestable Status as a result of its section 15 affidavit with the Patent and Trademark Office.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] According to former Texas A&M Athletic Director Bill Byrne, he contacted the Chicago Bears and Buffalo Bills about halting their "12th Man" themes.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Byrne stated that, "they responded quickly with our requests to stop using our Twelfth Man trademark".
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Texas A&M sent requests to stop using the phrase to the Seattle Seahawks in both 2004 and 2005.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] The Seahawks did not respond to the requests.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] In January 2006, Texas A&M filed a trademark infringement lawsuit against the Seattle Seahawks and in May 2006, the dispute was settled out of court.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] Neither side admitted any fault or liability.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] In the agreement, the Seahawks licensed the phrase in exchange for $100,000, along with public acknowledgement as to Texas A&M's ownership rights of the phrase, and an additional annual fee.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] The compensation amounted to $5,000 per year.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] The agreement, which expired in 2016, limited the Seahawks' usage to seven western states and forbid them from selling any "12th Man" merchandise.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] In August 2015, the Seahawks shifted towards calling their fans the "12s", and replaced their "Home of the 12th Man" stadium sign with a new "Home of the 12s" sign.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] On November 12, 2015, Texas A&M filed suit against the Indianapolis Colts after repeated cease and desist requests were ignored by the NFL team.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] In August 2016, the Seahawks agreed to a new five-year trademark licensing agreement with Texas A&M.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] As part of the agreement, the Seahawks agreed to pay Texas A&M $140,000 for limited rights to use the trademarked term.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] This agreement, like the previous agreement, prohibits the Seahawks from using the "12th Man" term on any merchandise.
[src:association-football/12th-man-football] The new agreement, however, also prohibits Seattle from using the term on social media, nor are they allowed to use the term on any signage within their stadium, including their Ring of Honor.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:association-football/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:association-football/1820s-in-football] The following are events in the 1820s decade which are relevant to the development of football.
[src:association-football/1830s-in-association-football] The following are events in the 1830s decade which are relevant to the development of association football.
[src:association-football/1830s-in-association-football] All events happened in English football unless specified otherwise.
[src:association-football/1840s-in-association-football] The following are events in the 1840s decade which are relevant to the development of association football.
[src:association-football/1850s-in-association-football] The following are events in the 1850s decade which are relevant to the development of association football.
[src:association-football/1850s-in-association-football] Included are events in closely related codes, such as the Sheffield Rules.
[src:association-football/1860s-in-association-football] The following are events in the 1860s decade which are relevant to the development of association football.
[src:association-football/1860s-in-association-football] There was constant discussion about the rules throughout this decade and several codes were in use.
[src:association-football/1860s-in-association-football] The Football Association (the FA) was founded in 1863 and its rules eventually prevailed.
[src:association-football/1860s-in-association-football] Points at issue among the various associations included offside, the throw-in, the corner kick, the crossbar and the now-obsolete touch down.
[src:association-football/1860s-in-association-football] Among the clubs founded in the 1860s were Notts County, Nottingham Forest, Queen's Park FC, Sheffield Wednesday, Stoke City and Kilmarnock.
[src:association-football/association-football] The objective of the game is to score more goals than the opposing team by moving the ball beyond the goal line into a rectangular-framed goal defended by the opponent.
[src:association-football/association-football] Traditionally, the game has been played over two 45-minute halves, for a total match time of 90 minutes.
[src:association-football/association-football] With an estimated 250 million players active in over 200 countries and territories, it is the world's most popular sport.
[src:association-football/association-football] Association football is played in accordance with the Laws of the Game, a set of rules that has been in effect since 1863 and maintained by the International Football Association Board (IFAB) since 1886.
[src:association-football/association-football] The game is played with a football that is 68–70 cm (27–28 in) in circumference.
[src:association-football/association-football] When the ball is in play, the players mainly use their feet, but may also use any other part of their body, except for their hands or arms, to control, strike, or pass the ball; the head, chest, and thighs are commonly used.
[src:association-football/association-football] Only the goalkeepers may use their hands and arms, but only within their own penalty area.
[src:association-football/association-football] Depending on the format of the competition, an equal number of goals scored may result in a draw being declared with 1 point awarded to each team, or the game may go into extra time or a penalty shoot-out.
[src:association-football/association-football] Internationally, association football is governed by FIFA.
[src:association-football/association-football] Under FIFA, there are six continental confederations: AFC, CAF, CONCACAF, CONMEBOL, OFC, and UEFA.
[src:association-football/association-football] National associations (e.g. the FA in England, U.S.
[src:association-football/association-football] Soccer in the United States, etc.) are responsible for managing the game in their own countries both professionally and at an amateur level, and coordinating competitions in accordance with the Laws of the Game.
[src:association-football/association-football] The most prestigious senior international competition is the FIFA World Cup.
[src:association-football/association-football] The men's World Cup is the most-viewed sporting event in the world, surpassing the Olympic Games.
[src:association-football/association-football] The most prestigious competition in European club football is the UEFA Champions League, which attracts an extensive television audience worldwide.
[src:association-football/association-football] The final of the men's Champions League is the most-watched annual sporting event in the world.
[src:association-football/association-football] Association football is part of a family of football games that emerged from various ball games played worldwide since antiquity.
[src:association-football/association-football] The word "association" in this term refers to the Football Association (the FA), founded in London in 1863, which published the first set of rules for the sport that same year.
[src:association-football/association-football] The term was coined to distinguish the type of football played in accordance with the FA rules from other types that were gaining popularity at the time, particularly rugby football.
[src:association-football/association-football] The term *soccer* comes from Oxford "-er" slang, which was prevalent at the University of Oxford in England from about 1875, and is thought to have been borrowed from the slang of Rugby School.
[src:association-football/association-football] Initially spelt *assoccer* (a shortening of "association"), it was later reduced to the modern spelling.
[src:association-football/association-football] Early alternative spellings included *socca* and *socker*.
[src:association-football/association-football] This form of slang also gave rise to *rugger* for rugby football, *fiver* and *tenner* for five pound and ten pound notes, and the now-archaic *footer* that was also a name for association football.
[src:association-football/association-football] A notable exception is New Zealand, where in the first two decades of the 21st century, under the influence of international television, "football" has been gaining prevalence, despite the dominance of other types of football, namely rugby union and rugby league.
[src:association-football/association-football] FIFA has stated that soccer originated in Britain, starting around the eighth century, and that no historical connection exists with any game played in antiquity outside Europe.
[src:association-football/association-football] The modern rules of association football are based on the mid-19th century efforts to standardise the widely varying forms of football played in the public schools of England.
[src:association-football/association-football] Kicking ball games arose independently multiple times across multiple cultures.
[src:association-football/association-football] The Chinese competitive game **cuju** (蹴鞠, literally "kickball"; also known as *tsu chu*) resembles modern association football as well as a mix of basketball and volleyball.
[src:association-football/association-football] This is the earliest form of a kicking game for which there is historical evidence.
[src:association-football/association-football] The game was first recorded as in exercise in the Zhan Guo Ce, a military history from the Han dynasty.
[src:association-football/association-football] **Cuju** players would pass the ball around, having to avoid it touching the ground at any point.
[src:association-football/association-football] It was then passed to a designated player, who attempted to kick it through the *fengliu yan*, a circular goal atop 10–11 meter poles.
[src:association-football/association-football] During the Han dynasty (206 BCE – 220 CE), **cuju** games were standardised and rules were established.
[src:association-football/association-football] The Silk Road facilitated the transmission of *cuju* outside of China, especially the form of the game popular in the Tang dynasty, the period when the inflatable ball was invented and replaced the stuffed ball.
[src:association-football/association-football] Other East Asian games include **kemari** in Japan and **chuk-guk** in Korea, both influenced by *cuju*.
[src:association-football/association-football] **Kemari** originated after the year 600 during the Asuka period.
[src:association-football/association-football] It was a ceremonial rather than a competitive game, and involved the kicking of a *mari*, a ball made of animal skin.
[src:association-football/association-football] In North America, *pasuckuakohowog* was a ball game played by the Algonquians; it was described as "almost identical to the kind of folk football being played in Europe at the same time, in which the ball was kicked through goals".
[src:association-football/association-football] In the Middle Ages, one notable game with similarities to modern football was *calcio storico fiorentino*, which originated in Florence, Italy.
[src:association-football/association-football] Another medieval sport that can be considered a form of early football is *la soule* (or *choule*), played in France from the 12th century, in which the ball was propelled by hands, feet, and sticks.
[src:association-football/association-football] As with pre-codified mob football, the antecedent of all modern football codes, these medieval games involved more handling of the ball than kicking it.
[src:association-football/association-football] The Cambridge rules, first drawn up at the University of Cambridge in 1848, were particularly influential in the development of subsequent codes, including association football.
[src:association-football/association-football] The Cambridge rules were written at Trinity College, Cambridge, at a meeting attended by representatives from Eton, Harrow, Rugby, Winchester, and Shrewsbury schools.
[src:association-football/association-football] During the 1850s, many clubs unconnected to schools or universities were formed throughout the English-speaking world to play various forms of football.
[src:association-football/association-football] Some came up with their own distinct codes of rules, most notably the Sheffield Football Club, formed by former public school pupils in 1857, which led to the formation of a Sheffield FA in 1867.
[src:association-football/association-football] In 1862, John Charles Thring of Uppingham School also devised an influential set of rules.
[src:association-football/association-football] These ongoing efforts contributed to the formation of the Football Association (the FA) in 1863, which first met on the morning of 26 October 1863 at the Freemasons' Tavern in Great Queen Street, London.
[src:association-football/association-football] The only school to be represented on this occasion was Charterhouse.
[src:association-football/association-football] The Freemasons' Tavern was the setting for five more meetings of the FA between October and December 1863; the English FA eventually issued the first comprehensive set of rules named Laws of the Game, forming modern football.
[src:association-football/association-football] The laws included bans on running with the ball in hand and hacking (kicking an opponent in the shins), tripping and holding.
[src:association-football/association-football] Eleven clubs, under the charge of FA secretary Ebenezer Cobb Morley, ratified the original thirteen laws of the game.
[src:association-football/association-football] The sticking point was hacking, which a twelfth club at the meeting, Blackheath FC, had wanted to keep, resulting in their withdrawal from the FA.
[src:association-football/association-football] Other English rugby clubs followed this lead and did not join the FA, and instead in 1871, along with Blackheath, formed the Rugby Football Union.
[src:association-football/association-football] The 1863 FA rules included handling of the ball by "marks" and the lack of a crossbar, making the game remarkably similar to Victorian rules football, which was being developed around the same time in Australia.
[src:association-football/association-football] The Sheffield FA played by its own rules until the 1870s, with the FA absorbing some of its rules until there was little difference between the games.
[src:association-football/association-football] The world's oldest football competition is the FA Cup, which was founded by the footballer and cricketer Charles W.
[src:association-football/association-football] Alcock, and has been contested by English teams since 1872.
[src:association-football/association-football] The first official international football match also took place in 1872, between Scotland and England in Glasgow, again at the instigation of Alcock.
[src:association-football/association-football] England is also home to the world's first football league, which was founded in Birmingham in 1888 by Aston Villa director William McGregor.
[src:association-football/association-football] The original format contained 12 clubs from the Midlands and Northern England.
[src:association-football/association-football] The Laws of the Game are determined by the International Football Association Board (IFAB).
[src:association-football/association-football] The board was formed in 1886 after a meeting in Manchester of the Football Association, the Scottish Football Association, the Football Association of Wales, and the Irish Football Association.
[src:association-football/association-football] FIFA, the international football body, was formed in Paris in 1904 and declared that they would adhere to the Laws of the Game of the Football Association.
[src:association-football/association-football] The growing popularity of the international game led to the admittance of FIFA representatives to the IFAB in 1913.
[src:association-football/association-football] The board consists of four representatives from FIFA and one representative from each of the four British associations.
[src:association-football/association-football] For most of the 20th century, Europe and South America were the dominant regions in association football.
[src:association-football/association-football] The FIFA World Cup, inaugurated in 1930, became the main stage for players of both continents to show their worth and the strength of their national teams.
[src:association-football/association-football] In the second half of the century, the European Cup and the Copa Libertadores were created, and the champions of these two club competitions would contest the Intercontinental Cup to prove which team was the best in the world.
[src:association-football/association-football] In the 21st century, South America has continued to produce some of the best footballers in the world, but its clubs have fallen behind the still dominant European clubs, which often sign the best players from Latin America and elsewhere.
[src:association-football/association-football] Meanwhile, football has improved in Africa, Asia, and North America, and nowadays, these regions are at least on equal grounds with South America in club football.
[src:association-football/association-football] Football is played at a professional level all over the world.
[src:association-football/association-football] Millions of people regularly go to football stadiums to follow their favourite teams, whilst billions more watch the game on television or on the internet.
[src:association-football/association-football] A very large number of people also play football at an amateur level.
[src:association-football/association-football] According to a survey conducted by FIFA published in 2001, over 240 million people from more than 200 countries regularly play football.
[src:association-football/association-football] Football has the highest global television audience in sport.
[src:association-football/association-football] In many parts of the world, football evokes great passions and plays an important role in the life of individual fans, local communities, and even nations.
[src:association-football/association-football] Ryszard Kapuściński says that Europeans who are polite, modest, or humble fall easily into rage when playing or watching football games.
[src:association-football/association-football] By contrast, football is widely considered to have been the final proximate cause for the Football War in June 1969 between El Salvador and Honduras.
[src:association-football/association-football] The sport also exacerbated tensions at the beginning of the Croatian War of Independence of the 1990s, when a match between Dinamo Zagreb and Red Star Belgrade degenerated into rioting in May 1990.
[src:association-football/association-football] The popularity of association football has been connected to identity fusion with replacement fandom collective identities.
[src:association-football/association-football] Women's association football has historically seen opposition, with national associations severely curbing its development and several outlawing it completely.
[src:association-football/association-football] Nevertheless, women have been playing football and similar games for as long as such games have existed.
[src:association-football/association-football] Frescoes from the Han dynasty (25–220 CE) depict female figures playing the ancient Chinese game *cuju*.
[src:association-football/association-football] There are also reports of annual football matches played by women in Midlothian, Scotland, during the 1790s.
[src:association-football/association-football] There is documented evidence of women's early involvement in association football.
[src:association-football/association-football] Informal matches between Scotland and England are reported to have taken place in 1881, but are not officially recognised by the respective football associations.
[src:association-football/association-football] The first women's match recorded by the Scottish Football Association took place in 1892 in Glasgow.
[src:association-football/association-football] In England, the first recorded game of football between women took place in 1895.
[src:association-football/association-football] The best-documented early European team was founded by activist Nettie Honeyball in England in 1894: the British Ladies' Football Club.
[src:association-football/association-football] Honeyball considered women's involvement in football as part of the emancipation movement.
[src:association-football/association-football] She and others like her paved the way for women's football.
[src:association-football/association-football] However, the women's game was frowned upon by the British football associations and continued without their support.
[src:association-football/association-football] It has been suggested that this was motivated by a perceived threat to the "masculinity" of the game.
[src:association-football/association-football] Women's football became popular on a large scale at the time of the First World War, when female employment in heavy industry spurred the growth of the game, much as it had done for men decades earlier.
[src:association-football/association-football] The most successful team of the era was Dick, Kerr Ladies F.C. of Preston, England.
[src:association-football/association-football] They played in one of the first women's international matches against a French XI team in 1920, and also made up most of the England team against a Scottish Ladies XI in the same year, winning 22–0.
[src:association-football/association-football] In the early 20th century, women's football in the United Kingdom was mostly associated with charity matches.
[src:association-football/association-football] Players and football writers have argued that this ban was, in fact, due to envy of the large crowds that women's matches attracted, and because the FA had no control over the money made from the women's game.
[src:association-football/association-football] The FA ban led to the formation of the short-lived English Ladies Football Association and play moved to rugby grounds.
[src:association-football/association-football] Women's football also faced bans in several other countries, notably in Brazil from 1941 to 1979, in France from 1941 to 1970, and in West Germany from 1955 to 1970.
[src:association-football/association-football] In spite of the resistance from governing bodies, British women continued to play football.
[src:association-football/association-football] Restrictions against female participation in the sport began to be reduced in the late 1960s and the 1970s.
[src:association-football/association-football] The Italian women's football league was established in 1968.
[src:association-football/association-football] In December 1969, the Women's Football Association was formed in England, with the sport eventually becoming the most prominent team sport for women in the United Kingdom.
[src:association-football/association-football] Two unofficial women's World Cups were organised by the FIEFF in 1970 and in 1971.
[src:association-football/association-football] Also in 1971, UEFA members voted to officially recognise women's football, while the Football Association rescinded the ban that prohibited women from playing on association members' pitches in England.
[src:association-football/association-football] The first Asian Women's Championship happened in 1975, initially without the approval of the AFC, but later recognised by them.
[src:association-football/association-football] Women's football still faces many struggles, but its worldwide growth has seen major competitions being launched at both the national and international levels, mirroring the men's competitions.
[src:association-football/association-football] The FIFA Women's World Cup was inaugurated in 1991: the first tournament was held in China, featuring 12 teams from the six confederations.
[src:association-football/association-football] The World Cup has been held every four years since; by 2019, it had expanded to 24 national teams, and 1.12 billion viewers watched the competition.
[src:association-football/association-football] Four years later, FIFA targeted the 32-team 2023 Women's World Cup at an audience of 2 billion, while more than 1.5 million tickets were sold, setting a Women's World Cup record.
[src:association-football/association-football] Women's football has been an Olympic event since 1996.
[src:association-football/association-football] North America is the dominant region in women's football, with the United States winning the most FIFA Women's World Cups and Olympic tournaments.
[src:association-football/association-football] Europe and Asia come second and third in terms of international success, and the women's game has been improving in South America.
[src:association-football/association-football] Association football is played in accordance with a set of rules known as the Laws of the Game.
[src:association-football/association-football] The game is played using a spherical ball of 68–70 cm (27–28 in) circumference, known as the *football* (or *soccer ball*).
[src:association-football/association-football] Two teams of eleven players each compete to get the ball into the other team's goal (between the posts and under the bar), thereby scoring a goal.
[src:association-football/association-football] There are situations where a goal can be disallowed, such as an offside call or a foul in the build-up to the goal.
[src:association-football/association-football] The team that has scored more goals at the end of the game is the winner; if both teams have scored an equal number of goals then the game is a draw.
[src:association-football/association-football] Each team is led by a captain who has only one official responsibility as mandated by the Laws of the Game: to represent their team in the coin toss before kick-off or penalty kicks.
[src:association-football/association-football] The primary law is that players other than goalkeepers may not deliberately handle the ball with their hands or arms during play, though they must use both their hands during a throw-in restart.
[src:association-football/association-football] Although players usually use their feet to move the ball around, they may use any part of their body (notably, "heading" with the forehead) other than their hands or arms.
[src:association-football/association-football] Within normal play, all players are free to play the ball in any direction and move throughout the pitch, though players may not pass to teammates who are in an offside position.
[src:association-football/association-football] During gameplay, players attempt to create goal-scoring opportunities through individual control of the ball, such as by dribbling, passing the ball to a teammate, and by taking shots at the goal, which is guarded by the opposing goalkeeper.
[src:association-football/association-football] Opposing players may try to regain control of the ball by intercepting a pass or through tackling the opponent in possession of the ball; however, physical contact between opponents is restricted.
[src:association-football/association-football] Football is generally a free-flowing game, with play stopping only when the ball has left the field of play or when play is stopped by the referee for an infringement of the rules.
[src:association-football/association-football] After a stoppage, play recommences with a specified restart.
[src:association-football/association-football] At a professional level, most matches produce only a few goals.
[src:association-football/association-football] For example, the 2022–23 season of the English Premier League produced an average of 2.85 goals per match.
[src:association-football/association-football] The Laws of the Game do not specify any player positions other than goalkeeper, but a number of specialised roles have evolved.
[src:association-football/association-football] Broadly, these include three main categories: strikers, or forwards, whose main task is to score goals; defenders, who specialise in preventing their opponents from scoring; and midfielders, who dispossess the opposition and keep possession of the ball to pass it to the forwards on their team.
[src:association-football/association-football] Players in these positions are referred to as outfield players, to distinguish them from the goalkeeper.
[src:association-football/association-football] These positions are further subdivided according to the area of the field in which the player spends the most time.
[src:association-football/association-football] For example, there are central defenders and left and right midfielders.
[src:association-football/association-football] The ten outfield players may be arranged in any combination.
[src:association-football/association-football] The number of players in each position determines the style of the team's play; more forwards and fewer defenders creates a more aggressive and offensive-minded game, while the reverse creates a slower, more defensive style of play.
[src:association-football/association-football] While players typically spend most of the game in a specific position, there are few restrictions on player movement, and players can switch positions at any time.
[src:association-football/association-football] The layout of a team's players is known as a *formation*.
[src:association-football/association-football] Defining the team's formation and tactics is usually the prerogative of the team's manager.
[src:association-football/association-football] There are seventeen laws in the official Laws of the Game, each containing a collection of stipulations and guidelines.
[src:association-football/association-football] The same laws are designed to apply to all levels of football for both sexes, although certain modifications for groups such as juniors, seniors and people with physical disabilities are permitted.
[src:association-football/association-football] The laws are often framed in broad terms, which allow flexibility in their application depending on the nature of the game.
[src:association-football/association-football] The Laws of the Game are published by FIFA, but are maintained by the IFAB.
[src:association-football/association-football] In addition to the seventeen laws, numerous IFAB decisions and other directives contribute to the regulation of association football.
[src:association-football/association-football] Within the United States, Major League Soccer used a distinct ruleset during the 1990s, and the NFHS and NCAA still use rulesets that are comparable to, but different from, the IFAB Laws.
[src:association-football/association-football] Each team consists of a maximum of eleven players (excluding substitutes), one of whom must be the goalkeeper.
[src:association-football/association-football] Competition rules may state a minimum number of players required to constitute a team, which is usually seven.
[src:association-football/association-football] Goalkeepers are the only players allowed to play the ball with their hands or arms, provided they do so within the penalty area in front of their own goal.
[src:association-football/association-football] Though there are a variety of positions in which the outfield (non-goalkeeper) players are strategically placed by a coach, these positions are not defined or required by the Laws.
[src:association-football/association-football] The basic equipment or *kit* players are required to wear includes a shirt, shorts, socks, footwear and adequate shin guards.
[src:association-football/association-football] Wearing an athletic supporter with protective cup is recommended for male players by medical experts and professionals.
[src:association-football/association-football] Headgear is not a required piece of equipment, but players may choose to wear it to protect themselves from head injury.
[src:association-football/association-football] Players are forbidden to wear or use anything that is dangerous to themselves or another player, such as jewellery or watches.
[src:association-football/association-football] The goalkeeper must wear clothing that is easily distinguishable from that worn by the other players and the match officials.
[src:association-football/association-football] A number of players may be replaced by substitutes during the course of the game.
[src:association-football/association-football] The maximum number of substitutions permitted in most competitive international and domestic league games is five in 90 minutes, with each team being allowed one more if the game should go into extra-time; the permitted number may vary in other competitions or in friendly matches.
[src:association-football/association-football] Common reasons for a substitution include injury, tiredness, ineffectiveness, a tactical switch, or timewasting at the end of a finely poised game.
[src:association-football/association-football] In standard adult matches, a player who has been substituted may not take further part in a match.
[src:association-football/association-football] IFAB recommends "that a match should not continue if there are fewer than seven players in either team".
[src:association-football/association-football] Any decision regarding points awarded for abandoned games is left to the individual football associations.
[src:association-football/association-football] A game is officiated by a referee, who has "full authority to enforce the Laws of the Game in connection with the match to which he has been appointed" (Law 5), and whose decisions are final.
[src:association-football/association-football] The referee is assisted by two assistant referees.
[src:association-football/association-football] In many high-level games there is also a fourth official who assists the referee and may replace another official should the need arise.
[src:association-football/association-football] Goal line technology is used to measure if the whole ball has crossed the goal-line thereby determining whether a goal has been scored or not; this was brought in to prevent controversy.
[src:association-football/association-football] Video assistant referees (VAR) have also been increasingly introduced in high-level matches to assist officials through video replays to correct clear and obvious mistakes.
[src:association-football/association-football] There are four types of calls that can be reviewed: mistaken identity in awarding a red or yellow card, goals and whether there was a violation during the build-up, direct red card decisions, and penalty decisions.
[src:association-football/association-football] The ball is spherical with a circumference of between 68 and 70 cm (27 and 28 in), a weight in the range of 410 to 450 g (14 to 16 oz), and a pressure between 0.6 and 1.1 standard atmospheres (8.5 and 15.6 pounds per square inch) at sea level.
[src:association-football/association-football] In the past the ball was made up of leather panels sewn together, with a latex bladder for pressurisation, but modern balls at all levels of the game are now synthetic.
[src:association-football/association-football] As the Laws were formulated in England, and were initially administered solely by the four British football associations within IFAB, the standard dimensions of a football pitch were originally expressed in imperial units.
[src:association-football/association-football] The Laws now express dimensions with approximate metric equivalents (followed by traditional units in brackets), though use of imperial units remains popular in English-speaking countries with a relatively recent history of metrication (or only partial metrication), such as Britain.
[src:association-football/association-football] The length of the pitch, or field, for international adult matches is in the range of 100–110 m (110–120 yd) and the width is in the range of 64–75 m (70–80 yd).
[src:association-football/association-football] Fields for non-international matches may be 90–120 m (100–130 yd) in length and 45–90 m (50–100 yd) in width, provided the pitch does not become square.
[src:association-football/association-football] In 2008, the IFAB initially approved a fixed size of 105 m (115 yd) long and 68 m (74 yd) wide as a standard pitch dimension for international matches; however, this decision was later put on hold and was never actually implemented.
[src:association-football/association-football] The longer boundary lines are *touchlines*, while the shorter boundaries (on which the goals are placed) are *goal lines*.
[src:association-football/association-football] A rectangular goal is positioned on each goal line, midway between the two touchlines.
[src:association-football/association-football] The inner edges of the vertical goal posts must be 7.32 m (24 ft) apart, and the lower edge of the horizontal crossbar supported by the goal posts must be 2.44 m (8 ft) above the ground.
[src:association-football/association-football] Nets are usually placed behind the goal, but are not required by the Laws.
[src:association-football/association-football] In front of the goal is the penalty area.
[src:association-football/association-football] This area is marked by the goal line, two lines starting on the goal line 16.5 m (18 yd) from the goalposts and extending 16.5 m (18 yd) into the pitch perpendicular to the goal line, and a line joining them.
[src:association-football/association-football] This area has a number of functions, the most prominent being to mark where the goalkeeper may handle the ball and where a penalty foul by a member of the defending team becomes punishable by a penalty kick.
[src:association-football/association-football] Other markings define the position of the ball or players at kick-offs, goal kicks, penalty kicks and corner kicks.
[src:association-football/association-football] A standard adult football match consists of two halves of 45 minutes each.
[src:association-football/association-football] Each half runs continuously, meaning that the clock is not stopped when the ball is out of play.
[src:association-football/association-football] There is usually a 15-minute half-time break between halves.
[src:association-football/association-football] The end of the match is known as full-time.
[src:association-football/association-football] The referee is the official timekeeper for the match, and may make an allowance for time lost through substitutions, injured players requiring attention, or other stoppages.
[src:association-football/association-football] This added time is called "additional time" in FIFA documents, but is most commonly referred to as *stoppage time* or *injury time*, while *lost time* can also be used as a synonym.
[src:association-football/association-football] The duration of stoppage time is at the sole discretion of the referee.
[src:association-football/association-football] Stoppage time does not fully compensate for the time in which the ball is out of play, and a 90-minute game typically involves about an hour of "effective playing time".
[src:association-football/association-football] The referee alone signals the end of the match.
[src:association-football/association-football] In matches where a fourth official is appointed, towards the end of the half, the referee signals how many minutes of stoppage time they intend to add.
[src:association-football/association-football] The fourth official then informs the players and spectators by holding up a board showing this number.
[src:association-football/association-football] The signalled stoppage time may be further extended by the referee.
[src:association-football/association-football] Added time was introduced because of an incident in 1891 during a match between Stoke and Aston Villa.
[src:association-football/association-football] Trailing 1–0 with two minutes remaining, Stoke were awarded a penalty kick.
[src:association-football/association-football] Villa's goalkeeper deliberately kicked the ball far out of play; by the time it was recovered, the clock had run out and the game was over, leaving Stoke unable to attempt the penalty.
[src:association-football/association-football] The same rule also states that the duration of either half is extended until a penalty kick to be taken or retaken is completed; thus, no game can end with an uncompleted penalty.
[src:association-football/association-football] Due to the relatively high ambient temperatures in some regions, cooling breaks for the players were introduced.
[src:association-football/association-football] Breaks could take place at the referee's discretion after the 30th minute of each half if the wet-bulb globe temperature exceeded 32 °C (90 °F); the breaks would last 3 minutes, with this time made up by an extended period of stoppage time at the end of the half.
[src:association-football/association-football] In league competitions, games may end in a draw.
[src:association-football/association-football] In knockout competitions where a winner is required, various methods may be employed to break such a deadlock; some competitions may invoke replays.
[src:association-football/association-football] A game tied at the end of regulation time may go into extra time, which consists of two further 15-minute periods.
[src:association-football/association-football] If the score is still tied after extra time, some competitions allow the use of penalty shoot-outs (previously known in the Laws of the Game as "kicks from the penalty mark") to determine which team will progress to the next stage of the tournament or be the champion.
[src:association-football/association-football] Goals scored during extra time periods count towards the final score of the game, but kicks from the penalty mark are only used to decide the team that progresses to the next part of the tournament, with goals scored in a penalty shoot-out not making up part of the final score.
[src:association-football/association-football] In competitions using two-legged matches, each team competes at home once, with an aggregate score from the two matches deciding which team progresses.
[src:association-football/association-football] Where aggregates are equal, the away goals rule may be used to determine the winners, in which case the winner is the team that scored the most goals in the leg they played away from home.
[src:association-football/association-football] If the result is still equal, extra time and potentially a penalty shoot-out are required.
[src:association-football/association-football] Under the Laws, the two basic states of play during a game are *ball in play* and *ball out of play*.
[src:association-football/association-football] From the beginning of each playing period with a kick-off until the end of the playing period, the ball is in play at all times, except when either the ball leaves the field of play, or play is stopped by the referee.
[src:association-football/association-football] Players are cautioned with a yellow card, and dismissed from the game with a red card.
[src:association-football/association-football] A foul occurs when a player commits an offence listed in the Laws of the Game while the ball is in play.
[src:association-football/association-football] The offences that constitute a foul are listed in Law 12.
[src:association-football/association-football] Handling the ball deliberately, tripping an opponent, or pushing an opponent, are examples of "penal fouls", punishable by a direct free kick or penalty kick depending on where the offence occurred.
[src:association-football/association-football] Other fouls are punishable by an indirect free kick.
[src:association-football/association-football] The referee may punish a player's or substitute's misconduct by a caution (yellow card) or dismissal (red card).
[src:association-football/association-football] A second yellow card in the same game leads to a red card, which results in a dismissal.
[src:association-football/association-football] A player given a yellow card is said to have been "booked", the referee writing the player's name in their official notebook.
[src:association-football/association-football] If a player has been dismissed, no substitute can be brought on in their place and the player may not participate in further play.
[src:association-football/association-football] Misconduct may occur at any time, and while the offences that constitute misconduct are listed, the definitions are broad.
[src:association-football/association-football] In particular, the offence of "unsporting behaviour" may be used to deal with most events that violate the spirit of the game, even if they are not listed as specific offences.
[src:association-football/association-football] A referee can show a yellow or red card to a player, substitute, substituted player, and to non-players such as managers and support staff.
[src:association-football/association-football] Rather than stopping play, the referee may allow play to continue if doing so will benefit the team against which an offence has been committed.
[src:association-football/association-football] This is known as "playing an advantage".
[src:association-football/association-football] The referee may "call back" play and penalise the original offence if the anticipated advantage does not ensue within "a few seconds".
[src:association-football/association-football] Even if an offence is not penalised due to advantage being played, the offender may still be sanctioned for misconduct at the next stoppage of play.
[src:association-football/association-football] The referee's decision in all on-pitch matters is considered final.
[src:association-football/association-football] The score of a match cannot be altered after the game, even if later evidence shows that decisions (including whether a goal was awarded or not) were incorrect.
[src:association-football/association-football] Along with the general administration of the sport, football associations and competition organisers also enforce good conduct in wider aspects of the game, dealing with issues such as comments to the press, clubs' financial management, doping, age fraud and match fixing.
[src:association-football/association-football] Most competitions enforce mandatory suspensions for players who are sent off in a game.
[src:association-football/association-football] Some on-field incidents, if considered very serious (such as allegations of racial abuse), may result in competitions deciding to impose heavier sanctions than those normally associated with a red card.
[src:association-football/association-football] Some associations allow for appeals against player suspensions incurred on-field if clubs feel a referee was incorrect or unduly harsh.
[src:association-football/association-football] Sanctions for such infractions may be levied on individuals or on clubs as a whole.
[src:association-football/association-football] Penalties may include fines, point deductions (in league competitions) or even expulsion from competitions.
[src:association-football/association-football] For example, the English Football League deduct 12 points from any team that enters financial administration.
[src:association-football/association-football] Among other administrative sanctions are penalties against game forfeiture.
[src:association-football/association-football] Teams that forfeit a game or are forfeited against are awarded a technical loss or win.
[src:association-football/association-football] The recognised international governing body of football (and associated games, such as futsal and beach soccer) is FIFA.
[src:association-football/association-football] The FIFA headquarters are located in Zürich, Switzerland.
[src:association-football/association-football] National associations (or national federations) oversee football within individual countries.
[src:association-football/association-football] 211 national associations are affiliated both with FIFA and with their respective continental confederations.
[src:association-football/association-football] Other national associations may be members of continental confederations but otherwise not participate in FIFA competitions.
[src:association-football/association-football] While FIFA is responsible for organising international competitions and enforcing most international regulations, the Laws of the Game are set by the IFAB, where each of the four UK associations holds one vote and FIFA collectively holds four votes.
[src:association-football/association-football] International competitions in association football principally consist of two varieties: competitions involving representative national teams or those involving clubs based in multiple nations and national leagues.
[src:association-football/association-football] *International football*, without qualification, most often refers to the former.
[src:association-football/association-football] In the case of international club competition, it is the country of origin of the clubs involved, not the nationalities of their players, that renders the competition international in nature.
[src:association-football/association-football] The major international competition in football and the most prestigious is the World Cup, organised by FIFA.
[src:association-football/association-football] This competition has taken place every four years since 1930, with the exception of the 1942 and 1946 tournaments, which were cancelled because of World War II.
[src:association-football/association-football] As of 2022, over 200 national teams compete in qualifying tournaments within the scope of continental confederations for a place in the finals.
[src:association-football/association-football] The finals tournament involved 32 national teams (expanding to 48 teams for the 2026 tournament) competing over a four-week period.
[src:association-football/association-football] The World Cup is the world's most widely viewed and most followed sporting event, with the 2022 tournament estimated to be watched by 5 billion people, more than 60% of the global population.
[src:association-football/association-football] The 1958 World Cup saw the emergence of Pelé as a global sporting star, a period that coincided with "the explosive spread of television, which massively amplified his presence everywhere".
[src:association-football/association-football] The current champions are Argentina, who won their third title at the 2022 tournament in Qatar.
[src:association-football/association-football] The FIFA Women's World Cup has been held every four years since 1991.
[src:association-football/association-football] Under the tournament's current format that was expanded in 2023, national teams vie for 31 slots in a three-year qualification phase, while the host nation's team enters automatically as the 32nd slot.
[src:association-football/association-football] The current champions are Spain, after winning their first title in the 2023 tournament.
[src:association-football/association-football] There has been a football tournament at every Summer Olympic Games since 1900, except at the 1932 games in Los Angeles when FIFA and the International Olympic Committee (IOC) had disagreed over the status of amateur players.
[src:association-football/association-football] Before the inception of the World Cup, the Olympics (especially during the 1920s) were the most prestigious international event.
[src:association-football/association-football] Originally, the tournament was for amateurs only.
[src:association-football/association-football] As professionalism spread around the world, the gap in quality between the World Cup and the Olympics widened.
[src:association-football/association-football] The countries that benefited most were the Soviet Bloc countries of Eastern Europe, where top athletes were state-sponsored while retaining their status as amateurs.
[src:association-football/association-football] Between 1948 and 1980, 23 out of 27 Olympic medals were won by Eastern Europe, with only Sweden (gold in 1948 and bronze in 1952), Denmark (bronze in 1948 and silver in 1960) and Japan (bronze in 1968) breaking their dominance.
[src:association-football/association-football] For the 1984 Los Angeles Games, the IOC allowed professional players to compete.
[src:association-football/association-football] Since 1992, male competitors must be under 23 years old, although since 1996, three players over the age of 23 have been allowed per squad.
[src:association-football/association-football] A women's tournament was added in 1996; in contrast to the men's event, full international sides without age restrictions play the women's Olympic tournament.
[src:association-football/association-football] After the World Cup, the most important international football competitions are the continental championships, which are organised by each continental confederation and contested between national teams.
[src:association-football/association-football] These are the European Championship (UEFA), the Copa América (CONMEBOL), the Africa Cup of Nations (CAF), the Asian Cup (AFC), the Gold Cup (CONCACAF) and the Nations Cup (OFC).
[src:association-football/association-football] These competitions are not strictly limited to members of the continental confederations, with guest teams from other continents sometimes invited to compete.
[src:association-football/association-football] The FIFA Confederations Cup was contested by the winners of all six continental championships, the current FIFA World Cup champions, and the country which was hosting the next World Cup.
[src:association-football/association-football] This was generally regarded as a warm-up tournament for the upcoming FIFA World Cup and did not carry the same prestige as the World Cup itself.
[src:association-football/association-football] The tournament was discontinued following the 2017 edition, with its calendar slot replaced by an expanded FIFA Club World Cup.
[src:association-football/association-football] The Finalissima was revived in 2022, and is contested between the Copa América and European Championship winners.
[src:association-football/association-football] The UEFA Nations League and the CONCACAF Nations League were introduced in the late 2010s to replace international friendlies during the two-year cycle between major tournaments.
[src:association-football/association-football] The most prestigious competitions in club football are the respective continental championships, which are generally contested between national champions, for example, the UEFA Champions League in Europe and the Copa Libertadores in South America.
[src:association-football/association-football] The winners of each continental competition contest the FIFA Intercontinental Cup, held annually, and the FIFA Club World Cup, held once every four years.
[src:association-football/association-football] In each country, football clubs are usually federated in associations or leagues that organise official tournaments among themselves, from which the champion of each country and the teams that will participate in international club tournaments emerge.
[src:association-football/association-football] There is no single system of competitions, and each national league organises them according to its own traditions.
[src:association-football/association-football] The governing bodies in each country operate league systems in a domestic season, normally comprising several divisions, in which the teams gain points throughout the season depending on results, usually three points for a win, one for a draw and zero for a defeat.
[src:association-football/association-football] Teams are put into tables, placed in order according to points accrued.
[src:association-football/association-football] In the Old World (Africa, Asia and Europe), it is common for each team to play every other team in its league at home and away in each season, in a round-robin tournament.
[src:association-football/association-football] At the end of a season, which typically runs from August to May, the top team is declared the champion.
[src:association-football/association-football] The top few teams may be promoted to a higher division, and one or more of the teams finishing at the bottom are relegated to a lower division.
[src:association-football/association-football] The teams finishing at the top of a country's league may also be eligible to play in international club competitions in the following season.
[src:association-football/association-football] Most countries supplement the league system with one or more "cup" competitions organised on a knock-out basis.
[src:association-football/association-football] These include the domestic cup, which may be open to all eligible teams in a country's league system—both professional and amateur—and is organised by the national federation.
[src:association-football/association-football] Some countries' top divisions feature highly-paid star players; in smaller countries, lower divisions, and many women's clubs, players may be part-timers with a second job, or amateurs.
[src:association-football/association-football] The top five European leagues – Premier League (England), Bundesliga (Germany), La Liga (Spain), Serie A (Italy), and Ligue 1 (France) – attract most of the world's best players and, during the 2006–07 season, each of these leagues had a total wage cost in excess of €600 million.
[src:association-football/association-football] These leagues also generated a combined €17.2 billion in revenue in the 2021–22 season from television contracts, matchday tickets, sponsorships, and other sources.
[src:association-football/association-football] In the 2022–23 season, clubs in Europe's "big five" leagues had an aggregate wage cost of €13 billion, with each league spending more than €1.8 billion in wages.
[src:association-football/association-football] In contrast, the combined revenue of these leagues was €19.6 billion.
[src:association-football/association-football] Variants of association football have been codified for teams of reduced size, such as five-a-side football; for non-traditional playing environments, including beach soccer, futsal and indoor soccer; and for athletes with disabilities (Paralympic football).
[src:association-football/association-football] Street football can be played with only minimal equipment – a basic game can be played on almost any open area of reasonable size with just a ball made from almost any material and items to mark the positions of the goalposts.
[src:association-football/association-football] Such informal games can have team sizes that vary from eleven-a-side, can use a limited or modified subset of the official rules, and can be self-officiated by the players.
